New Roman'; font-size:12pt">: </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In some jurisdictions</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> there is what they c</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">all a vacant land tax. If you have a piece of land that</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> has been sitting idle for a number of years</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> a tax is imposed on it, and there are arguments for and against that. I think it is a fairly indirect mechanism. You can say that you tax land to raise the holding cost of keeping it vaca</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">nt. It</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> would take a long time </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">for that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">to work through</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. A </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">more direct mechanism is to have almost an inverse compulsory purchas</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">e order. It is not the state acquiring it but the state saying</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">after a period of time</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, “Y</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ou</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">’ve</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> had your chanc</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">e to make use of this land. You haven’t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> made use of it. This now has to go to auction and someone else can</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> have it.”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36.85pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Q348</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Chair:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Surely, in those circumstances</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> you can quite easily h</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ave a carousel of owners. I</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">t is not held by the same group, trust or structure for any length of time</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, but after six months it is</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> sold to another front company and it keeps rotating.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Professor Adams</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">: </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">You could deal with that through the terms of the contract and the property rights to give an implied option to the public authority</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><spa